        },
        "subject": {
          "reference": "Patient/[Number]"
        },
        "valueString": "The patient was a 65-year-old man admitted due to repetitive drug-resistant VT episodes and decompensated heart failure. He had a history of cardiac sarcoidosis and a cardiac resynchronization therapy device implanted. Despite the administration of multiple medications, VTs could not be controlled, and he was admitted to our hospital. Electroanatomical mapping and RFA were performed to manage the VT storm, targeting low voltage zones and/or abnormal electrograms such as those with fragmented and double potentials. After the procedure, the clinical VT could not be induced. However, a different VT emerged two days later, and he required intubation, sedation, and cardiopulmonary support. A second ablation session was performed, and the VT was eliminated. The patient, however, died from deterioration of his heart failure 12 days after the procedure. A postmortem examination of the heart was performed revealed ablation lesions that were mainly located on the interventricular septum and inferior wall of the left ventricle."
      }
